title.narrative: Small Infrastructure for Water and Sanitation (SIWS)

description.narrative: The Small Infrastructure for Water and Sanitation (SIWS) Program in Kosovo works in four of the country's poorest municipalities in partnership with three of the best performing regional water companies. This five-year program (2008-12) is installing, rehabilitating, expanding, and upgrading water systems in four municipalities in Kosovo. The program is expected to generate $3 million in cost-share from regional water companies, municipalities, and communities. SIWS has established partnerships with the municipal authorities of Peja, Gllogoc, Lipjan, and Malisheva, and their corresponding RWCs - Hidrodrini, Hidroregjioni Jugor, and Pristina. Over the life of the program, SIWS will mobilize nearly $8 million, including cost-sharing, in project works benefiting over 85,000 Kosovans with an improved water supply.

description.narrative: The Kosovo Local Effective Governance Activity project seeks to help strengthen the ability of local governments in Kosovo to effectively engage and serve their residents, particularly non-majority populations that often feel excluded from local information sharing and decision making. The five-year project, awarded to ICMA by the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID), has two objectives: 1) Improve equitable, efficient, and transparent municipal governance that responds to citizens priorities with a focus on non-majority participation in democratic structures. 2) Increase active citizen participation of both majority and non-majority communities in municipal structures.

Objectives for Kosovo: Project Objectives: Improved equitable, efficient, and transparent municipal governance that responds to citizens priorities with a focus on non-majority participation in democratic structures; Strengthen local municipal governments and administration to improve service provision to both majority and non-majority communities; Improve the ability of municipalities to articulate their needs to the central-level government; Strengthen municipal transparency and outreach to all citizens; Strengthen central-level capacities related to outreach and governance to provide better support for municipalities in addressing the needs of non-majority communities and improve municipal service delivery; Facilitate associations between municipalities. Increased civic participation in municipal structures among both majority and non-majority communities. Increase interaction between majority and non-majority communities through joint priority setting. Empower all communities to engage with municipalities and hold them accountable

description.narrative: Justice Matters is a three-year activity to improve access to justice for all, inclusive of disadvantaged and marginalized groups, by strengthening the institutions, actors, and processes for providing legal aid services and legal information. Through this activity, USAID aims to: Strengthening the Capacity of Kosovo's Legal Aid System; Enhance the Quality and Responsivness of Legal Aid Service; and Strengthen Legal Literacy and Citizens Empowerment.

Objectives for Kosovo: Justice Matters is a three-year activity to improve access to justice for all, inclusive of disadvantaged and marginalized groups, by strengthening the institutions, actors, and processes for providing legal aid services and legal information. Through this activity, USAID aims to: 1) Strengthening the Capacity of Kosovo's Legal Aid System: The Justice Matters activity will focus on systems to strengthen the capacity of the Kosovos legal aid system in a manner that is holistic and sustainable. Our interventions will improve financial management, develop the institutional capacity of the Legal Aid Council and Free Legal Aid Agency (FLAA), enable provider accreditation and mobilization, and facilitate inter-institutional coordination. 2) Enhance the Quality and Responsivness of Legal Aid Service: The Justice Matters activity will focus on the supply of legal aid services to enhance their availability, quality, and responsiveness to the justice needs of communities. Our interventions will develop a coordinated needs assessment methodology; integrate legal aid work into law school curriculum through live clinics; increase access to services across Kosovo; and increase the professionalism of legal aid practitioners. The quantity and quality of legal aid will increase, connecting a network of providers and law students to expand FLAA reach and tailoring services to meet the specific needs of communities, including women, minorities, and other vulnerable groups. 3) Strengthen Legal Literacy and Citizens Empowerment: Activity will focus on increasing informed demand for legal aid services by improving legal literacy and empowering citizens, especially vulnerable groups. Interventions will provide actionable legal information to communities and vulnerable groups, leveraging existing informational platforms and activating a network of civil society organizations (CSOs), grassroots organizations, and young people to deliver information. In addition, interventions will support coalition building to conduct effective budget advocacy on behalf of the legal aid system. Citizens will have access to concrete information on their legal rights enabling them to seek enforcement of those rights in the justice system and CSOs will coalesce to support advocacy for increase resources for the legal aid system.

description.narrative: The Responsive, Effective, Accountable Governance activity seeks to advance these principles by.improving legislative and political responsiveness s to citizen needs. These issues, if not addressed with, can threaten political stability. This activity will improve the National Assembly and political party responsiveness to.citizens needs by improving Member of Parliament (MP) performance profiles on.the Assembly's website, thereby providing attendance, statements, voting.patterns, and financial disclosures. The activity will continue to conduct public opinion research to help beneficiaries use the data in their outreach strategies, caucus legislative plans, party policy development, and gender and youth inclusion strategies. The activity will also continue to support MP efforts to inform the public about legislative business and parliamentary oversight of the executive branch, with the aim of increased opportunities for public input into and scrutiny of legislation. The activity will also increase the number of local women leaders skilled to assume greater leadership positions.

The longer-term.threat posed by a sense of exclusion from democratic institutions and civic and.economic participation is even more corrosive to Kosovo's democratic.institutions, internal stability, and European integration ambitions. With FY.2020 funds, USAID's Up to Youth activity will address youth's vulnerability to.social exclusion by supporting interventions that will: increase their sense of.responsibility; lead participatory analyses of problems and find solutions;.demonstrate leadership; and engage actively. Up to Youth is mobilizing youth to.be a force for positive change. The activity is equipping youth with the.necessary skills to play active roles in their communities and the economy. Up.to Youth will also work with local partners to foster an environment for youth.to engage in a positive and meaningful way. Youth participants will finalize.Community Asset Mapping with their particular communities and will be further.equipped with soft/life skills. These skills will help youth demonstrate leadership.and analyze data to identify youth-related challenges and issues in their.communities. This activity aligns with ICS objective 2.2 Enhance the quality of.Kosovo's human capital, particularly among its youth, to support economic.development and meet the labor skills required by the private sector. In.addition, it aligns with JRS Goals 2 and 4, respectively: Strengthening and.Balancing the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Relationship; and, Upholding.Western Democratic principles and Institutions... ...

description.narrative: (Kosovo): .Kosovo's civil society has made significant progress over the last 20 years, largely with USAID assistance. However, gaps in the capacity and accountability of local civil society organizations (CSOs) and public institutions, as well as low social trust, hamper the ability of civil society to be an effective bridge between the citizens and their government. With FY22 funds, the Citizen Engagement Activity will work with Kosovo's civil society to embrace new approaches to working with their constituencies, to adopt a more strategic perspective on both intra and inter-sectoral partnerships, and to diversify its resource and partner base. Specifically, the activity will foster connections between youth activists and CSOs, build CSO community mobilization and fundraising skills, improve the legal environment and develop tech solutions for civil society's financial transparency and for individual and corporate philanthropy, support implementation of Government-Civil society cooperation strategy, and promote skilled volunteerism. The activity aligns with ICS objective 2.2: Institutions' transparency and ability to respond to all citizens' needs; deliver quality services; implement laws, regulations, and court decisions; and reduce corruption is enhanced and with JRS Goal 3.1: Promote good governance and defend strong, accountable, and resilient democracies that deliver for their citizens. This activity also aligns with CAATSA #5 by strengthening the capacity of CSOs to represent citizens' interests, which in turn will contribute to a constructive environment for Kosovo's development and prosperity. This activity contributes to the following directives and key issues: democracy directive and women, peace and security... .

description.narrative: (Kosovo): .With this activity, USAID will address behavioral, institutional, and cultural impediments to citizen engagement in order to rebuild citizens' confidence in Kosovo's social contract and facilitate a stronger citizen-government partnership. By strengthening mutual trust and encouraging greater collaboration between citizens and government, the activity will help better align municipal services with citizens' needs and expectations and support locally led and funded solutions to Kosovo's development. The implementer finalized a municipal needs assessments and focus groups with the citizens and municipal officials regarding public participation in five pilot municipalities. The selected needs for cooperation among the municipalities and citizens will be incorporated into municipality-specific action plans aimed at improving the practice and experience of public participation for both public officials and citizens. In Year 2 of the activity, the identified activities within the action plans will be implemented by the municipalities in direct cooperation with the communities. The ultimate goal is to introduce public participation processes that both the community and local administrations find valuable and feasible and will therefore sustain after the activity ends. The activity aligns with ICS objective 2.2 Institutions' transparency and ability to respond to all citizens' needs; deliver quality services; implement laws, regulations, and court decisions; and reduce corruption is enhanced and with JRS Goal 3.1: Promote good governance and defend strong, accountable, and resilient democracies that deliver for their citizens as well as JRS Objective 3.3: Prevent, expose, and reduce corruption. This activity contributes to the key issues:People-to-People Conflict Prevention and Peacebuilding,Gender Equality/Women's Empowerment-Secondary, Women, Peace and Security, andAdvancing Racial Equity/Supporting Underserved Communities..

description.narrative: The project supported Kosovo to improve the transparency and accountability of the municipal procurement process in all 38 municipalities. At the central level, the project worked with institutions that oversee public procurement, supervise municipal internal auditors, manage the municipal budgeting process, and oversee anti-corruption investigations. In addition, the project team built the capacity of civil society organizations to exercise citizen oversight municipal procurement in a watchdog role and to provide checks and balances by exposing corrupt practices and working with citizens and local governments as a partner in the process of procurement modernization. Building off that project, the Municipal Integrity Activity is working with central government oversight agencies, municipalities, and civil society, media, and private sector actors to advance reform in public procurement, with a renewed emphasis on budget planning, contract management, audit, integrity, and private sector engagement.

description.narrative: (Kosovo): Increased business competitiveness in the private sector requires the skills of a high-tech and agile 21st century workforce. A competitive workforce is also critical for the long-term economic growth of Kosovo. When young people are mobilized to acquire relevant skills and fair opportunities for democratic and economic engagement, there will be greater openings for the Kosovan private sector and youth to participate in civic and economic life. This activity will serve as a catalyst for promoting and encouraging stronger and more strategic relationships between the private sector, government, and academia; where curricula match market needs, policies reflect a more progressive and highly integrated education system, and where scalability can thrive with a highly-concentrated youth workforce that can raise Kosovo's economic competitiveness. This activity will build Kosovo's capacity to transform the orientation of vocational education, driven by the private sector, to advance economic growth. This activity aligns with ICS objective 3.1 Enhanced engagement and policy enactment in trade, regional economic integration, and private sector competitiveness helps Kosovo take ownership of its own prosperity, and objective 3.3 Kosovo's human capital enhanced through better integration of underserved communities and by equipping citizens with the skills needed for a modern economy and resilient democracy that attracts investment and reduces "brain drain." In addition, it aligns with JRS Goal 4.1: Build and equip a diverse, inclusive, resilient, and dynamic workforce and Objective 2.2: Support inclusive and sustainable economic growth and opportunity for communities around the globe. This activity contributes to the following key issues and directives: engagement of higher education institutions, private sector engagement, and democracy overlap..

title.narrative: Transformational Leadership Program - Scholarships and Partnerships

description.narrative: (Kosovo): The Transformational Leadership Program - Scholarships and Partnerships (TLP-SP) will continue to support Kosovo's largest public higher-education institution, the University of Prishtina, through a range of university-wide institution-building activities, including facilitating academic exchanges with Arizona State University, Indiana University, and the University of Minnesota. These links with the University of Prishtina will strengthen local capacities in modern teaching methodologies and research, as well as curriculum and course development, in line with local labor market demands. TLP-SP will also continue to support enrolled Master's-level students as well place remaining certificate-level recipients.

Objectives for Kosovo: The primary purpose of the program is to increase the number of educated professionals to strengthen Kosovos dynamic transition to a democratic, free market economy. Participatory democracy valuessuch as personal responsibility, accountability, entrepreneurship, and public actionhave yet to be fully absorbed and practiced by Kosovar society. Until these values are embedded in the culture, Kosovos development as a vibrant society may be jeopardized. Future leaders will be developed in critical areas that support diplomatic and assistance priorities identified by the Kosovo and U.S. governments. Key objectives include: Coordinated, collaborative oversight of the Transformational Leadership initiative through an advisory committee; Kosovo citizens receive U.S. post-graduate degrees and professional certification; and Improved university management and pedagogy in selected faculties of the University of Prishtina and/or other universities through partnerships and exchanges with American universities.

description.narrative: Support and strengthen the negotiation process and implement peace and reconciliation processes, accords and ceasefire agreements at track levels 1, 2 and 3, including support to indigenous peacebuilding efforts. For a peace/negotiations process to have a chance of success, it must entail building trust in the process, between parties, and among their constituents, with a special focus on including women. Illustrative activities include negotiation training; platform development; public opinion polling; facilitation activities; elder statesmen engagement; provision of international expert advice and knowledge; financial support to parties; multi-stakeholder dialogues; assistance with the design of peacebuilding training programs; support and maintenance of agreed verification mechanisms; support to complaint tracking mechanisms; and work with local and national government representatives to bring them closer to their constituencies.

description.narrative: (Kosovo): .While civil society has made significant progress in.the last 20 years with USAID assistance, Kosovo still has weak linkages between.governmental and non-governmental institutions and its citizenry. Hence,.with the new Civil Society Activity, USAID aims to strengthen the.accountability between the Government of Kosovo, civil society organizations.(CSOs), and citizens by increasing citizens' participation and decreasing CSO.and citizen donor dependency. With FY 2019 funds, USAID will strive to: increase.the ability of civil society to develop and implement people-centered.solutions; increase capacities of CSOs to mobilize and control assets in.developing and implementing solutions to challenges faced by their communities.(thus shifting from a donor-led agenda to a citizen-centered agenda); and.mobilize and leverage Government of Kosovo financial resources to strengthen.services based on citizen needs. This activity will also foster resource.diversification (from government, private donors, diaspora, etc.). USAID will also work with CSOs on financial self-reliance. The activity aligns with.JRS Goal 4.1, by seeking to strengthen the rule of law, separation of powers,.independent media, and civil society, in part through youth development. This.activity also aligns with CAATSA #5 with $500,000 allocated toward.strengthening the capacity of CSOs to represent citizens' interests, which in.turn will contribute to a constructive environment for Kosovo's development and.prosperity....

Objectives for Kosovo: Conduct complex advocacy and awareness campaigns in cooperation with stakeholders from diverse segments of society and government. Engage in drafting policy recommendations on democracy, governance, and economic empowerment issues, drawn from consultations with members of vulnerable populations, a wider base of citizens, and other relevant stakeholders. Monitor and track the implementation of targeted legislation, reforms, and initiatives of high importance to vulnerable and marginalized groups. Engagement for Equity focuses its support on:. Strengthening women in governance and economy. Empowering women through enhanced awareness of womens property rights. Increasing protection and awareness of LGBT community rights. Expanding participation of people with disabilities (PwD). Expanding youth participation/ Expand Youth Participation to counter violent extremism

description.narrative: Improve the capacity and sustainability of civil and criminal justice sector actors and institutions, enhance coordination amongst them, develop citizen demand for an effective and accountable justice system, and develop associations to advocate for all citizens. Justice sector actors and institutions include: police, border security, prosecutors, forensics experts, judges, court personnel, public defenders, corrections personnel, private bar, law schools, legal professional associations, and training institutions for each of them. Work towards an equitable justice system by ensuring equality before the law, fair trial standards, and other elements of procedural fairness. Ensure more equitable access to justice through innovations within and beyond the state system and through improvements in the quality and quantity of justice services, with a particular focus on women, youth, the poor, and other marginalized or vulnerable groups. Programs primarily focused on trafficking in persons or migrant smuggling should be included in element 5.3 under the Transnational Crime area in the Peace and Security Objective.

Objectives for Kosovo: The USAID Contract Law Enforcement (CLE) Program is a five-year program to improve rule of law in Kosovo and create a better business environment for economic development and investment. The program is built around two strategic goals: Assisting Kosovo institutions to improve the enforcement of civil judgments, while dramatically reducing the backlog of enforcement cases in the Kosovo court system and Helping the country develop and strengthen its contract and commercial law framework and systems, including for bankruptcy and mediation.

description.narrative: (Kosovo): Advancing Kosovo Together - U.S. Prime is a $7.6 million, three-year program that aims to increase constructive inter-ethnic cooperation and interaction, primarily between the Kosovo-Albanian majority and Kosovo-Serb population, which is vital to the security and stability of the Balkans. Using FY~2015 funds, interventions will include grassroots community exchanges, improved service provision by local administrations, and market integrations to improve overall value chains and encourage long-term economic integration and viability of non-majority businesses.

Objectives for Kosovo: AKT aims to increase constructive interethnic cooperation and interaction between Kosovos majority and minority populations, which is vital to the security and stability of the region. The program takes a holistic approach toward the integration of minority populations by partnering with municipalities and other government partners to support the engagement of targeted communities. In particular, the program works to improve conditions to enable ethnic minorities to actively engage in the work force and Government of Kosovo institutions while preserving and protecting their unique cultural heritage.

description.narrative: (Kosovo): .Enhancing competitiveness is essential for Kosovo to move up the economic value chain, connect with regional and global markets, and escape the "low to middle income trap" which will generate strong and sustainable prosperity and employment. With FY 2018 funds, the Empower Private Sector activity will continue to promote economic growth by developing more competitive small and medium-sized enterprises and fostering a more skilled workforce. Empower Private Sector will build on the work with various companies by increasing their productive capacities to meet market opportunities. A greater focus will be placed on providing technical expertise and capacity building to existing and additional beneficiaries to improve their competitiveness and to increase sales which leads to more jobs. Activities will be tailored to widen market connections and improve productivity and quality.Specific interventions will include technology upgrade, process line improvements, product quality certifications, skills training and internships for new workforce entrants, matchmaking events, trade fairs and B2B. Finally, FY 2018 funds will be used to further leverage private sector funds to expand market linkages as well as channel money for investment in high potential sectors. This activity aligns with JRS goal 2.2 by spurring on private sector led economic growth and employment, thus reducing vulnerability to economic coercion by making Kosovar firms and sectors more competitive. .. .... .

Objectives for Kosovo: The overarching goal of EMPOWER Private Sector is to increase competitiveness and facilitate inclusive job creation in selected growth-ready sectors: wood processing, apparel, ICT (information and communications technology), energy efficiency, outdoor tourism, and other opportunistic sectors. The program works closely with producers and service providers with potential to serve a larger market. Support includes: expanding buyer connections, increasing and improving production, addressing skills needs through specific training and internship programs, and facilitating finance.To address high levels of unemployment and to enhance a social inclusion agenda in the private sector, the support targets four priority populations: women, youth, ethnic minorities, and other vulnerable groups to address high levels of unemployment. The program supports a broad range of interventions that have a high job-creation impact.

description.narrative: (Kosovo): .Development of Kosovo's agriculture sector will promote economic growth by developing a more competitive agriculture sector.Livelihood through Agriculture promotes economic growth by reducing unemployment and balancing the county's trade deficit.By reducing imports of agricultural products,and increasing exports of high value perishable crops,(where US exports of fresh and frozen crops are not competitive due to the distance to European markets) a more robust agricultural sector will directly and indirectly provide new job opportunities, especially since approximately 70 percent of the rural population is dependent on agriculture as a source of income.This year AGRO will strengthen strategic partners so they have the ability to independently drive growth across the value chain of targeted high value crops.These partners are active in the value chains of soft fruit,medicinal and aromatic plants, top fruit and vegetable sectors.Assistance will help strategic partners expand market linkages within Kosovo and in export markets, reducing Kosovo's massive trade deficit and boosting job creation at all levels of the agricultural value chain.Resources will be directed towards compliance with international food safety standards for production and processing, and ensuring that strategic partners provide increasingly sound technical support to contracted producers.All interventions will be made through national associations and strategic partners.AGRO will emphasize partnerships with municipal and central governments. Funds will also integrate young graduates with an interest or background in agriculture within firms in the agricultural sector, which aligns with JRS goal 2.2 of promoting market-oriented economic and governance reforms by promoting reforms to the government's agricultural grants and subsidies while at the same time boosting economic growth, jobs, and resilience to economic coercion through more competitive farms and supply chains.... .

description.narrative: (Kosovo): .Public procurement accounts for up to 40 percent of Kosovo's budget. The Transparent, Effective, and Accountable Municipalities activity (TEAM) targets corruption in this sector by increasing the transparency and effectiveness of municipal public procurement systems. With FY 2020 funds, the activity will further consolidate and deepen gains in transparency and will strengthen the existing accountability and enforcement mechanisms. In FY 2020, TEAM will also expand the Kosovo public e-procurement platform and improve municipal project and contract management processes. TEAM will add two new modules to the e-platform-contract management and contractor's past performance report-in order to improve performance and accountability of the municipal contract managers. This directly responds to civil society's demand for greater transparency in public procurement and addresses citizens' dissatisfaction with the quality of municipal goods and services that is often attributed to poor contract management. USAID plans to scale up its direct support and proven successful anti-corruption efforts to ten additional municipalities. USAID will enhance transparency of public funds through improved interoperability between finance and procurement systems and develop training materials for judges and prosecutors on handling procurement fraud cases. USAID will also build the capacity of civil society to monitor public procurement processes, detect fraud, and refer cases to prosecution. TEAM will also continue preventing corruption in procurement and supporting fraud detection through improved audits and government compliance with audit findings. The activity aligns with JRS goal 4.2 Promote good governance, fight corruption, and counter human trafficking... .... .

description.narrative: The Kosovo Energy Security of Supply activity will improve Kosovo's energy security by building the capacity of the Ministry of Economic Development and providing a full range of long-term and quick response professional services across the Kosovo energy sector, with a focus on new power generation. description.narrative: (Kosovo): .This activity will continue to strengthen the linkages among citizens, parties, and the National Assembly to incentivize and orient the Government of Kosovo to address public interests in a more responsive manner. This will be achieved by: working on issue advocacy driven by women, youth, and minority communities, including Kosovo Serbs in the north; party policy development and coordination with parliamentary caucuses; improving informed lawmaking and effective oversight processes; and stronger observation of election processes. The program fosters participation of women, youth and minorities in politics as community activists, political party members, and elected representatives..

Objectives for Kosovo: The overall goal of this program is to strengthen linkages among citizens, political parties, and the Assembly to incentivize government bodies to be more responsive to public interests. To achieve this, the National Democratic Institute (NDI) has three mutually reinforcing objectives: To foster the participation of women, youth, and minorities in politics as community activists, political party members, and elected representatives; To increase both the quality and effectiveness of lawmaking and oversight in the Assembly; To heighten public engagement in the legislative and electoral process; To achieve these objectives, the program is working to promote integration of civic engagement throughout Kosovo. Targeted assistance includes: Working on issue-based advocacy driven by women, youth, and minority communities, particularly Kosovar Serbs in the North; party policy development and coordination with parliamentary caucuses; Improving informed lawmaking and effective oversight processes; and Improving stronger observation of election processes.

description.narrative: (Kosovo): Activity will continue to work on improving the integrity, accountability, and transparency in the justice system, while minimizing corruption. JSSP will continue to strengthen the efficiency and the effectiveness of the Kosovo Judicial Council (KJC) and courts. The activity will increase the independence of the KJC and the efficiency of Kosovo's courts and disciplinary bodies. It will continue to support the full functioning of judicial structures in the north of Kosovo, especially after their successful integration into the Kosovo system in October 2017. This support includes technical assistance and training to newly integrated judges and staff and support for the administration of the court. JSSP will also continue with technical assistance and capacity building for current and new Constitutional Court of Kosovo judges and administration. The activity will also work to increase the role of women in the justice system. As part of CATSSA goal 2, USAID will continue to strengthen Kosovo's independent judiciary through technical assistance to the KJC and courts and small grants to civil society and media to monitor the judiciary's reforms and survey court users to build upon reforms. Furthermore, technical assistance, coaching, and training will provide direct support to the KJC and the courts in the north to fully include them in the Kosovo judiciary by implementing case flow processes, management structures, and including the courts into processes within the KJC. The result of these activities is to ensure a fully functioning multi-ethnic court system in the north of Kosovo, an area particularly susceptible to false narratives from Russia. A fully functioning judiciary in Kosovo's north is critical to stabilizing the region given the north's porous borders and organized crime, which aligns with goal four of JRS "Uphold Western Democratic Principles and Institutions"..... ...

Objectives for Kosovo: USAIDs Justice System Strengthening Program, aims to: 1) Strengthen efficiency and effectiveness in the administration of justice and the delivery of quality services. USAID, through the Justice System Strengthening Program assists the Kosovo Judicial Council (KJC) and Kosovos courts in consolidating gains in efficiency and management at the court level. This is accomplished by facilitating the decentralization of administrative competencies and institutionalizing systems and tools for effective court and case management. Activities under this objective reduce case backlog and procedural obstacles to court efficiency and effectiveness. 2) Enhance the accountability and professionalism of the justice system The program works closely with the KJC, judges, and court staff in building capacity to deliver justice professionally and efficiently. It also promotes continuing education and public integrity initiatives as the foundation for a judiciary that is accessible, credible, and effective. 3) Support the functioning and the integration of judicial structures in the North USAID Justice System Strengthening Program supports the KJC and the courts in activating judicial structures in northern Kosovo based on the Justice Sector Agreement that was signed between the governments of Kosovo and Serbia in 2015. This agreement provides for the integration of institutions, court operations, and judicial resources in the north. This USAID program also assists individual courts in the region with case inventories and transfers, backlog reduction, case management, and capacity-building for judges and court staff.

title.narrative: Systems for Enforcing Agreements and Decisions (SEAD) Program

description.narrative: Since achieving independence in 2008, Kosovo has faced the challenge of establishing a system for enforcing legal agreements and court decisions that are necessary to stimulate domestic economic growth and foreign investment. In particular, the responsibility given to municipal court judges for executing utility bills and other minor claims has left the courts with large backlogs of civil cases and diverted resources from protecting the contract and property rights of citizens and businesses. As USAID's implementing partner for the SEAD Program, Checchi is working with local institutions to address these challenges through the introduction of stronger enforcement and dispute resolution mechanisms. Program components focus on promoting the acceptance and use of standardized contracts and binding obligations in commercial transactions, streamlining procedures for the enforcement of judgments, and developing an effective system for alternative dispute resolution (ADR) in Kosovo that is consistent with international standards.
